Business Brief -- MIP Properties Inc.:
   Bankruptcy Filing Is Mulled
   After Repayment Demand
"We continue to hope we can reach an acceptable agreement
with our bank. However, given the bank's proposed terms and.
. .stated lack of flexibility, we feel compelled to explore
these other alternatives," said Carl C. Gregory III, chairman
and chief executive officer.
   The trust's lender, Security Pacific National Bank, Los
Angeles, called the loan recently, after the trust defaulted
on certain terms. For the first nine months of last year, MIP
had a loss of $22 million, or $2.44 a share.